    <!-- Why US Citizens Choose a UK Ltd -->
    <section class="py-24 bg-white border-b border-gray-100">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 prose prose-lg prose-blue">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 tracking-tighter mb-6">Why US Citizens Are Forming UK Limited Companies in 2026</h2>
            <p>For American entrepreneurs looking to expand beyond the domestic market, a UK Limited Company offers strategic advantages that a US LLC cannot always match in Europe. The UK shares a common language, a robust Double Taxation Treaty with the USA, and a fintech ecosystem that makes remote banking and cross-border payments far more practical.</p>
            <p>Key reasons US founders choose a <strong>UK Ltd for non-residents</strong> — and why the semantic cluster around <strong>uk company tax non resident director</strong>, <strong>uk registered office address non resident</strong>, and <strong>uk business bank account non resident</strong> matters:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>European market access:</strong> A UK company is a "first-class citizen" for Stripe UK, PayPal Europe, and EU supplier contracts. European buyers trust a "Limited" company over a foreign LLC.</li>
                <li><strong>Banking without borders:</strong> Open a <a href="/blog/business-banking-uk-ltd-non-residents">UK business bank account</a> through Wise or Mercury without ever visiting the UK. Hold GBP, USD, and EUR in one account.</li>
                <li><strong>ACSP-verified compliance:</strong> Under 2026 ECCTA rules, all directors must pass biometric identity verification through an Authorized Corporate Service Provider. We handle this entirely via our mobile app.</li>
                <li><strong>Tax treaty benefits:</strong> The UK-US Double Taxation Treaty prevents you from being taxed twice on the same income. Your UK company pays Corporation Tax (19%–25%), and you receive a credit against your US tax liability.</li>
                <li><strong>Forex and trading:</strong> Active traders use a UK Ltd to receive <a href="/get-help-forming-a-uk-ltd">prop firm payouts</a> and access FCA-regulated brokers with a recognized corporate entity.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </section>

